AI DEVELOPMENT ROADMAP
Project: 30‑Layer Cognitive Architecture
Status: Active
Maintainer: Peter

This roadmap outlines realistic development timelines for each layer of the 30‑page architecture, based on current AI research, open‑source capabilities, and free‑tier compute limits. It also tracks which layers can be built today and which require future breakthroughs.

------------------------------------------------------------
SECTION 1 — TIMELINE BY LAYER GROUP
------------------------------------------------------------

PAGES 1–10 — CURRENT TECH (0–3 years)
These layers are fully achievable using free tools, open‑source models, and local compute.
Includes:
- Tool‑using agents
- Memory graphs
- Multi‑step planners
- Multi‑agent basics
- Self‑debugging loops
- Workflow automation

PAGES 11–15 — ADVANCED AUTONOMY (3–7 years)
Partially achievable today. Full versions require better free models and more stable long‑term memory systems.
Includes:
- Persistent memory
- Autonomous task loops
- Self‑evaluation
- Multi‑agent collaboration
- Local world‑models

PAGES 16–20 — COLLECTIVE INTELLIGENCE (5–12 years)
Prototype versions possible on free tiers. Full versions require stable agent coordination and shared memory worlds.
Includes:
- Swarm cognition
- Shared memory spaces
- Agent negotiation
- Emergent problem‑solving

PAGES 21–24 — SELF‑MODELING SYSTEMS (10–20 years)
Mostly research‑level. Small‑scale simulations possible.
Includes:
- Internal state awareness
- Self‑reflection loops
- Predictive self‑simulation
- Identity persistence

PAGES 25–30 — EMERGENT SUPER‑SYSTEMS (20–40 years)
Conceptual design possible today. Full realization requires new compute, new math, and safe recursive self‑improvement.
Includes:
- Recursive self‑improvement
- Hive‑mind architectures
- Distributed cognition
- Self‑rewriting systems

------------------------------------------------------------
